WEBVTT

00:00:00.080 --> 00:00:02.480
For 500,000 years, we've had essentially

00:00:02.480 --> 00:00:04.400
the same cognitive architecture. And

00:00:04.400 --> 00:00:06.879
today, I want to talk about a leap that

00:00:06.879 --> 00:00:08.240
we can make, all of us, even

00:00:08.240 --> 00:00:10.719
non-engineers, can make in 2026 that

00:00:10.719 --> 00:00:13.440
will help us to build a second brain

00:00:13.440 --> 00:00:16.000
with AI in a way that's never been

00:00:16.000 --> 00:00:18.240
possible before. But first, let me set

00:00:18.240 --> 00:00:21.199
the stage. Why does this matter? Look, a

00:00:21.199 --> 00:00:23.119
second brain doesn't have to exist

00:00:23.119 --> 00:00:24.480
because you're lazy. It's not because

00:00:24.480 --> 00:00:26.320
you don't care. It's fundamentally

00:00:26.320 --> 00:00:29.039
because your brain was never designed to

00:00:29.039 --> 00:00:31.679
be a storage system. Brains are designed

00:00:31.679 --> 00:00:33.520
to think. And every time you force a

00:00:33.520 --> 00:00:35.280
brain to remember something, instead of

00:00:35.280 --> 00:00:36.880
letting it think of something new,

00:00:36.880 --> 00:00:39.200
you're paying a tax that you don't see.

00:00:39.200 --> 00:00:41.280
And that tax shows up in real ways. It

00:00:41.280 --> 00:00:43.440
shows up in relationships that cool off

00:00:43.440 --> 00:00:45.280
because you forgot what someone told you

00:00:45.280 --> 00:00:47.120
that mattered to them. It shows up in

00:00:47.120 --> 00:00:49.280
projects that fail in the same way you

00:00:49.280 --> 00:00:52.160
predicted at 11:00 p.m. 3 weeks ago,

00:00:52.160 --> 00:00:54.239
except you forgot to write it down. and

00:00:54.239 --> 00:00:56.000
you got to be right and then you still

00:00:56.000 --> 00:00:57.680
got to suffer the consequences cuz you

00:00:57.680 --> 00:00:59.520
couldn't prevent it. It shows up in the

00:00:59.520 --> 00:01:01.600
background hum of constant open loops in

00:01:01.600 --> 00:01:03.199
your brain. Things you never finished

00:01:03.199 --> 00:01:04.640
that you are just on the edge of

00:01:04.640 --> 00:01:06.880
remembering that low-grade anxiety of

00:01:06.880 --> 00:01:09.280
don't forget to do this running as a

00:01:09.280 --> 00:01:12.000
thread that you cannot close because you

00:01:12.000 --> 00:01:14.080
never put that loop anywhere reliable

00:01:14.080 --> 00:01:16.240
and you can't trust a journaling system

00:01:16.240 --> 00:01:18.159
to remember. So here's what I want you

00:01:18.159 --> 00:01:20.560
to understand about this moment in our

00:01:20.560 --> 00:01:22.080
history. For hundreds of thousands of

00:01:22.080 --> 00:01:24.159
years, human beings have had roughly the

00:01:24.159 --> 00:01:26.400
same cognitive architecture. We can hold

00:01:26.400 --> 00:01:27.920
about four to seven things in working

00:01:27.920 --> 00:01:29.520
memory. There's a reason why phone

00:01:29.520 --> 00:01:31.840
numbers are about the length they are.

00:01:31.840 --> 00:01:34.320
We're terrible at retrieval. We're great

00:01:34.320 --> 00:01:36.320
at pattern recognition when the patterns

00:01:36.320 --> 00:01:38.079
are in front of us. And we're really bad

00:01:38.079 --> 00:01:39.759
at pattern recognition when the patterns

00:01:39.759 --> 00:01:42.240
are scattered like they so often are at

00:01:42.240 --> 00:01:44.000
work across six months of

00:01:44.000 --> 00:01:46.079
half-remembered conversations. Every

00:01:46.079 --> 00:01:48.799
productivity system ever invented has

00:01:48.799 --> 00:01:51.119
been a workaround for our human brain

00:01:51.119 --> 00:01:53.360
limitations. Writing itself is a

00:01:53.360 --> 00:01:55.200
workaround. So, filing cabinets,

00:01:55.200 --> 00:01:57.119
rolodexes, to-do lists, journaling

00:01:57.119 --> 00:01:59.200
systems, all of it has been an attempt

00:01:59.200 --> 00:02:01.680
to extend our biological memory into

00:02:01.680 --> 00:02:03.920
something that is more reliable. But

00:02:03.920 --> 00:02:06.560
here's what's different about 2026. For

00:02:06.560 --> 00:02:09.440
the first time in human history, we have

00:02:09.440 --> 00:02:11.840
access to systems that do not just

00:02:11.840 --> 00:02:13.760
passively store information, but

00:02:13.760 --> 00:02:16.080
actively work against that information

00:02:16.080 --> 00:02:18.959
we give it while we sleep and do other

00:02:18.959 --> 00:02:21.120
things. Systems that can classify,

00:02:21.120 --> 00:02:23.440
route, or summarize or surface or nudge

00:02:23.440 --> 00:02:25.680
without us having to remember to do any

00:02:25.680 --> 00:02:27.599
of those activities. This is not an

00:02:27.599 --> 00:02:29.120
incremental improvement. This is an

00:02:29.120 --> 00:02:31.360
entirely new capability in the history

00:02:31.360 --> 00:02:33.120
of human cognition. And the most

00:02:33.120 --> 00:02:35.760
important part is in 2026, you don't

00:02:35.760 --> 00:02:37.519
have to be an engineer to build a second

00:02:37.519 --> 00:02:39.280
brain. So let me go through what has

00:02:39.280 --> 00:02:41.120
actually changed and why this moment

00:02:41.120 --> 00:02:43.120
matters. And I think this is the time if

00:02:43.120 --> 00:02:44.879
you don't have a second brain, it's

00:02:44.879 --> 00:02:46.800
worth building one. So for years, the

00:02:46.800 --> 00:02:48.560
promise of a second brain was

00:02:48.560 --> 00:02:50.560
essentially just, hey, it's better

00:02:50.560 --> 00:02:52.879
storage. You pick a tool, maybe it's

00:02:52.879 --> 00:02:54.800
notion, maybe it's Obsidian, maybe it's

00:02:54.800 --> 00:02:56.800
Rome, maybe it's Evernote, and you

00:02:56.800 --> 00:02:59.280
capture your notes. Maybe you use AI to

00:02:59.280 --> 00:03:01.840
summarize, to search, and then nothing.

00:03:01.840 --> 00:03:03.760
the notes would pile up. You end up

00:03:03.760 --> 00:03:05.280
having to keep them very organized

00:03:05.280 --> 00:03:07.200
yourself or you stop trusting them. At

00:03:07.200 --> 00:03:09.360
some point, it becomes the company wiki

00:03:09.360 --> 00:03:11.920
that everyone looks at as a dump of old

00:03:11.920 --> 00:03:14.159
information. You stop using it and the

00:03:14.159 --> 00:03:16.080
system dies the death of so many of

00:03:16.080 --> 00:03:18.159
these storage solutions. I've watched

00:03:18.159 --> 00:03:20.800
this cycle repeat in personal systems

00:03:20.800 --> 00:03:23.440
and professional systems for well over a

00:03:23.440 --> 00:03:25.120
decade. And smart people, really

00:03:25.120 --> 00:03:27.360
motivated people, people who genuinely

00:03:27.360 --> 00:03:29.360
want to be organized tend to hit the

00:03:29.360 --> 00:03:31.599
same wall. The storage systems we have

00:03:31.599 --> 00:03:34.720
today work for about one in 20 people

00:03:34.720 --> 00:03:36.959
that I talk to on an ongoing daily

00:03:36.959 --> 00:03:38.640
basis. And those people are typically

00:03:38.640 --> 00:03:40.560
the most organized people I know. So you

00:03:40.560 --> 00:03:41.920
would think they need it the least, but

00:03:41.920 --> 00:03:43.200
they're so organized they can make it

00:03:43.200 --> 00:03:45.440
work for them. For the rest of us, it's

00:03:45.440 --> 00:03:47.040
a challenge. And the wall is not

00:03:47.040 --> 00:03:49.120
motivation. The wall is that traditional

00:03:49.120 --> 00:03:52.400
systems ask us to do cognitive work at

00:03:52.400 --> 00:03:55.120
exactly the wrong moment. They ask us to

00:03:55.120 --> 00:03:57.519
decide where a thought belongs when

00:03:57.519 --> 00:03:59.200
we're walking into a meeting. They ask

00:03:59.200 --> 00:04:01.200
us to tag it when we're driving. They

00:04:01.200 --> 00:04:03.040
ask us to name it properly when we're

00:04:03.040 --> 00:04:04.799
about to go to bed. They ask us to

00:04:04.799 --> 00:04:06.640
choose a folder in a taxonomy and a

00:04:06.640 --> 00:04:08.400
structure. And that's the moment when

00:04:08.400 --> 00:04:09.920
you frankly don't want that. You just

00:04:09.920 --> 00:04:11.439
want relief. You want someone else to do

00:04:11.439 --> 00:04:12.959
it. You don't want to organize. You want

00:04:12.959 --> 00:04:15.439
to capture it and move on. And so most

00:04:15.439 --> 00:04:17.519
of us do what every normal person does.

00:04:17.519 --> 00:04:19.199
We take a note somewhere. You stick it

00:04:19.199 --> 00:04:20.959
in Apple Notes and you tell yourself

00:04:20.959 --> 00:04:22.639
you'll organize it later, right? And

00:04:22.639 --> 00:04:24.960
later never comes. You have a pile of

00:04:24.960 --> 00:04:26.400
notes you don't trust, which means you

00:04:26.400 --> 00:04:28.320
stop putting notes in it. and the whole

00:04:28.320 --> 00:04:30.080
thing collapses. And so what's changed

00:04:30.080 --> 00:04:32.560
is that we're moving from AI inside your

00:04:32.560 --> 00:04:35.600
notes as a search tool to AI running a

00:04:35.600 --> 00:04:38.160
loop. And the difference is enormous. An

00:04:38.160 --> 00:04:41.360
AI loop means the system does work

00:04:41.360 --> 00:04:44.000
whether or not you feel motivated today.

00:04:44.000 --> 00:04:46.160
You capture a thought in 5 seconds. The

00:04:46.160 --> 00:04:48.240
system classifies it. It routes it to

00:04:48.240 --> 00:04:49.759
the right place. It extracts the

00:04:49.759 --> 00:04:51.680
relevant details. It writes it into a

00:04:51.680 --> 00:04:53.840
structured database. And then it nudges

00:04:53.840 --> 00:04:56.080
you every morning with what matters

00:04:56.080 --> 00:04:58.080
today. Then it reviews your week every

00:04:58.080 --> 00:04:59.919
Sunday and it tells you what's stuck,

00:04:59.919 --> 00:05:01.680
what's moving, what you should focus on

00:05:01.680 --> 00:05:04.080
next. You don't have to remember to use

00:05:04.080 --> 00:05:06.960
it. It just shows up. That's the shift

00:05:06.960 --> 00:05:09.280
from building a knowledge base to

00:05:09.280 --> 00:05:11.280
installing a behavior changing system.

00:05:11.280 --> 00:05:14.639
The center of gravity moves from you as

00:05:14.639 --> 00:05:16.000
the person who has to keep all of this

00:05:16.000 --> 00:05:18.400
on the rails to the loop helping you

00:05:18.400 --> 00:05:20.400
stay on the rails and stay organized.

00:05:20.400 --> 00:05:22.479
You get a genuine support structure.

00:05:22.479 --> 00:05:24.960
Now, this all sounds very theoretical. I

00:05:24.960 --> 00:05:27.120
am not a hypy person. I am not the

00:05:27.120 --> 00:05:28.800
person telling you to do this in early

00:05:28.800 --> 00:05:31.039
2024 when the tools aren't ready. I want

00:05:31.039 --> 00:05:34.639
to tell you now exactly what tools make

00:05:34.639 --> 00:05:38.400
this work today in 2026. The stack I

00:05:38.400 --> 00:05:40.080
would recommend if you are not an

00:05:40.080 --> 00:05:43.440
engineer is Slack plus notion plus

00:05:43.440 --> 00:05:46.160
Zapier plus Claude or Chat JPT. That's

00:05:46.160 --> 00:05:48.479
it. Four tools all of which you probably

00:05:48.479 --> 00:05:50.639
already have access to or can get access

00:05:50.639 --> 00:05:52.720
to in the next 10 minutes. Slack is your

00:05:52.720 --> 00:05:54.720
capture point. Almost everyone's in

00:05:54.720 --> 00:05:57.120
Slack already. You create one private

00:05:57.120 --> 00:05:59.520
channel just for you called SB Inbox or

00:05:59.520 --> 00:06:01.120
whatever you want to name it. And that's

00:06:01.120 --> 00:06:02.960
where you throw every single thought.

00:06:02.960 --> 00:06:05.199
One message per thought. No organizing,

00:06:05.199 --> 00:06:07.680
no tagging, no decisions. You type it or

00:06:07.680 --> 00:06:10.160
you paste it and you hit send. Notion is

00:06:10.160 --> 00:06:12.240
the storage layer. You create four

00:06:12.240 --> 00:06:15.199
simple databases. People, projects,

00:06:15.199 --> 00:06:18.080
ideas, and admin. Each one has a handful

00:06:18.080 --> 00:06:19.840
of field that the system is going to

00:06:19.840 --> 00:06:21.280
fill in automatically. like the date

00:06:21.280 --> 00:06:22.800
that you filed. This is a great field,

00:06:22.800 --> 00:06:24.960
right? And you then create a fifth

00:06:24.960 --> 00:06:28.080
database called the inbox log that acts

00:06:28.080 --> 00:06:29.759
as an audit trail for this system. And

00:06:29.759 --> 00:06:31.120
if you're wondering, how do I keep this

00:06:31.120 --> 00:06:33.039
straight? I can't remember this. This is

00:06:33.039 --> 00:06:35.680
a second brain. Well, good news. I made

00:06:35.680 --> 00:06:37.520
a whole guide for it and you can go and

00:06:37.520 --> 00:06:39.440
grab it on Substack and you don't have

00:06:39.440 --> 00:06:41.199
to remember this part. Zapier is your

00:06:41.199 --> 00:06:43.039
automation layer. It's the thing that

00:06:43.039 --> 00:06:45.120
wires everything together. When a

00:06:45.120 --> 00:06:46.880
message appears in your Slack channel,

00:06:46.880 --> 00:06:49.039
Zapier just sees it and it kicks off the

00:06:49.039 --> 00:06:50.639
workflow to pipe things into notion. And

00:06:50.639 --> 00:06:52.479
so the workflow calls an AI, it writes

00:06:52.479 --> 00:06:54.479
to notion, it fills out all those fields

00:06:54.479 --> 00:06:56.639
I described and then it replies back in

00:06:56.639 --> 00:06:58.960
Slack. You can also use make instead of

00:06:58.960 --> 00:07:00.960
Zapier if you want something that's

00:07:00.960 --> 00:07:03.199
cheaper. Same idea. The logic is

00:07:03.199 --> 00:07:05.520
identical. And Clott GPT ends up being

00:07:05.520 --> 00:07:07.199
your intelligence layer. It's what

00:07:07.199 --> 00:07:09.280
classifies your thought. It's extracts

00:07:09.280 --> 00:07:11.280
the relevant details. It decides where

00:07:11.280 --> 00:07:13.199
things should go. You give it a very

00:07:13.199 --> 00:07:16.560
specific prompt with say a JSON schema

00:07:16.560 --> 00:07:18.960
and it returns structured data that

00:07:18.960 --> 00:07:20.960
Zapier can then write directly into

00:07:20.960 --> 00:07:22.639
notion. And so the flow looks like this.

00:07:22.639 --> 00:07:25.280
Slack captures the stuff. You use Zapier

00:07:25.280 --> 00:07:27.680
to automate pulling that raw data out.

00:07:27.680 --> 00:07:29.840
Zapier then makes a call using your

00:07:29.840 --> 00:07:32.240
structured prompt to Chad GPT or to

00:07:32.240 --> 00:07:34.319
Claude and they provide the intelligence

00:07:34.319 --> 00:07:37.199
to structure this out into a useful

00:07:37.199 --> 00:07:39.280
complete entry that you can make into

00:07:39.280 --> 00:07:41.199
your second brain. And then that gets

00:07:41.199 --> 00:07:43.199
piped into notion. Everything else at

00:07:43.199 --> 00:07:45.280
that point is just configuration to make

00:07:45.280 --> 00:07:47.440
it feel like home to you. And so what I

00:07:47.440 --> 00:07:49.039
find genuinely exciting about this

00:07:49.039 --> 00:07:50.720
moment, it's not the nerdiness of

00:07:50.720 --> 00:07:53.039
hooking it up and getting like Zapier to

00:07:53.039 --> 00:07:54.960
talk to Slack and everything else. The

00:07:54.960 --> 00:07:57.039
patterns that make these systems work

00:07:57.039 --> 00:07:59.039
are the exciting thing because even

00:07:59.039 --> 00:08:01.120
though they're not particularly new and

00:08:01.120 --> 00:08:03.120
engineers have been building reliable

00:08:03.120 --> 00:08:05.520
automated systems for a while, we in the

00:08:05.520 --> 00:08:08.400
non-engineering world are just now at a

00:08:08.400 --> 00:08:10.960
point in 2026 where we can leverage

00:08:10.960 --> 00:08:13.360
these principles to build these kinds of

00:08:13.360 --> 00:08:16.400
systems without a single line of code.

00:08:16.400 --> 00:08:18.319
And so I want to be really explicit in

00:08:18.319 --> 00:08:20.479
this video and I want to teach you the

00:08:20.479 --> 00:08:22.319
principles that I use to design the

00:08:22.319 --> 00:08:24.560
system I just described. So you

00:08:24.560 --> 00:08:27.440
understand how this works and why it

00:08:27.440 --> 00:08:29.599
scales and you can apply this other

00:08:29.599 --> 00:08:31.039
places with AI. And so these are

00:08:31.039 --> 00:08:32.479
principles that govern how we make

00:08:32.479 --> 00:08:34.399
systems that scale, systems that don't

00:08:34.399 --> 00:08:36.240
break, systems that maintain trust over

00:08:36.240 --> 00:08:38.240
time. These are long-standing

00:08:38.240 --> 00:08:40.159
engineering principles, and we all need

00:08:40.159 --> 00:08:41.519
to know them now. And so I'm going to

00:08:41.519 --> 00:08:43.360
take this opportunity to say, here's the

00:08:43.360 --> 00:08:44.800
system. Here's the second brain, but

00:08:44.800 --> 00:08:46.640
also here's how you learn from this.

00:08:46.640 --> 00:08:48.560
Here are the engineering principles

00:08:48.560 --> 00:08:50.320
translated for non-engineers that you

00:08:50.320 --> 00:08:52.160
can latch on to. And when you understand

00:08:52.160 --> 00:08:54.880
these things, you can build things that

00:08:54.880 --> 00:08:57.200
used to require a principal engineer to

00:08:57.200 --> 00:08:58.720
implement. So here's the building

00:08:58.720 --> 00:09:00.480
blocks. Engineers have really fancy

00:09:00.480 --> 00:09:02.160
names for these things, but I'm going to

00:09:02.160 --> 00:09:03.920
give you plain language that actually

00:09:03.920 --> 00:09:06.080
make sense. There are about eight core

00:09:06.080 --> 00:09:07.839
pieces that make a second brain system

00:09:07.839 --> 00:09:09.200
work. And once you see them, you're

00:09:09.200 --> 00:09:10.720
going to recognize them in a bunch of

00:09:10.720 --> 00:09:12.320
other reliable systems, and that's going

00:09:12.320 --> 00:09:14.800
to help you build fluency that you will

00:09:14.800 --> 00:09:17.440
need with AI in 2026. The first building

00:09:17.440 --> 00:09:19.279
block is what I call the Dropbox.

00:09:19.279 --> 00:09:20.640
Engineers are going to call this the

00:09:20.640 --> 00:09:22.720
capture door or the ingress point. It's

00:09:22.720 --> 00:09:24.560
the one place you're allowed to throw

00:09:24.560 --> 00:09:26.640
things without thinking. It has to be

00:09:26.640 --> 00:09:28.240
frictionless. If capturing a thought

00:09:28.240 --> 00:09:29.839
takes more than a couple of seconds,

00:09:29.839 --> 00:09:31.040
you're actually not going to do it

00:09:31.040 --> 00:09:32.320
consistently despite your good

00:09:32.320 --> 00:09:33.920
intentions. It's not a moral failing.

00:09:33.920 --> 00:09:35.920
It's just human nature. So, you need one

00:09:35.920 --> 00:09:38.880
place, one action, one consistent habit.

00:09:38.880 --> 00:09:40.640
In this system, the Dropbox, say that

00:09:40.640 --> 00:09:42.800
five times fast, is a Slack channel

00:09:42.800 --> 00:09:45.200
called SB Inbox. You create it, you make

00:09:45.200 --> 00:09:47.360
it private, you pin a message explaining

00:09:47.360 --> 00:09:48.959
what goes in there. From then on,

00:09:48.959 --> 00:09:50.640
whenever a thought appears in your head

00:09:50.640 --> 00:09:52.640
that you don't want to lose, you open up

00:09:52.640 --> 00:09:54.000
Slack, you go to that channel, and you

00:09:54.000 --> 00:09:56.000
just type it in. One message, done.

00:09:56.000 --> 00:09:57.680
You're not allowed to have three capture

00:09:57.680 --> 00:09:59.680
points, you have only one, and it

00:09:59.680 --> 00:10:01.680
requires zero decisions. The second

00:10:01.680 --> 00:10:03.519
building block is the sorter. Engineers

00:10:03.519 --> 00:10:05.279
call this a classifier. They call it a

00:10:05.279 --> 00:10:07.920
router. It's the AI step that decides

00:10:07.920 --> 00:10:10.320
what bucket your thought belongs in

00:10:10.320 --> 00:10:12.399
without you having to think about it. Is

00:10:12.399 --> 00:10:14.480
this about a person, a project, an idea,

00:10:14.480 --> 00:10:16.399
some admin errand that you need to do?

00:10:16.399 --> 00:10:18.480
Here's why this matters. The number one

00:10:18.480 --> 00:10:20.720
reason second brains fail is they

00:10:20.720 --> 00:10:23.440
require taxonomy work at capture time.

00:10:23.440 --> 00:10:25.279
They force you to decide where something

00:10:25.279 --> 00:10:26.880
goes. And for non-engineers, that

00:10:26.880 --> 00:10:28.880
decision is where systems go to die.

00:10:28.880 --> 00:10:30.720
It's the blank canvas problem, the

00:10:30.720 --> 00:10:32.880
perfect structure fantasy, the slow

00:10:32.880 --> 00:10:34.640
drift into fiddling with folders instead

00:10:34.640 --> 00:10:36.480
of actually capturing thoughts. So, the

00:10:36.480 --> 00:10:38.160
sortter removes all of that entirely.

00:10:38.160 --> 00:10:40.079
You throw a raw thought at your Slack

00:10:40.079 --> 00:10:42.079
channel. Zapier picks it up and sends it

00:10:42.079 --> 00:10:44.399
to Claude or GPT with a classification

00:10:44.399 --> 00:10:46.880
prompt. The AI then figures out what it

00:10:46.880 --> 00:10:49.519
is, extracts the relevant details, names

00:10:49.519 --> 00:10:51.519
it something useful, and returns

00:10:51.519 --> 00:10:54.560
structured JSON. Classification is a

00:10:54.560 --> 00:10:57.040
solved problem this year in 2026. You

00:10:57.040 --> 00:10:58.800
can let the model do the sorting, and it

00:10:58.800 --> 00:11:01.040
will just work. The third building block

00:11:01.040 --> 00:11:03.040
is the form. Engineers call this the

00:11:03.040 --> 00:11:04.720
schema. They might call it a data

00:11:04.720 --> 00:11:06.560
contract. It's the set of fields your

00:11:06.560 --> 00:11:09.200
system promises to produce and store for

00:11:09.200 --> 00:11:11.680
each type of thing. So, for a person in

00:11:11.680 --> 00:11:13.440
your people database, this can mean the

00:11:13.440 --> 00:11:15.600
name, the context about who they are and

00:11:15.600 --> 00:11:17.440
how you know them, follow-ups that you

00:11:17.440 --> 00:11:19.279
need to remember for next time you talk,

00:11:19.279 --> 00:11:20.959
and a timestamp for when you last

00:11:20.959 --> 00:11:23.200
updated their entry. For a project, it

00:11:23.200 --> 00:11:25.040
can be the name, the status, which could

00:11:25.040 --> 00:11:26.800
be active or waiting or blocked or

00:11:26.800 --> 00:11:29.200
someday or done, the literal next action

00:11:29.200 --> 00:11:31.200
you need to take, and any relevant

00:11:31.200 --> 00:11:33.040
notes. If it's an idea, maybe it's a

00:11:33.040 --> 00:11:35.040
title, a oneliner that captures the core

00:11:35.040 --> 00:11:37.120
insight, and space for elaboration. So,

00:11:37.120 --> 00:11:38.800
why does this matter? Because without a

00:11:38.800 --> 00:11:40.399
consistent form, you're going to get

00:11:40.399 --> 00:11:42.320
messy notes that can't be reliably

00:11:42.320 --> 00:11:43.920
queried, that can't be reliably

00:11:43.920 --> 00:11:46.640
summarized or surfaced. Claude is not

00:11:46.640 --> 00:11:48.800
going to generate a useful daily digest

00:11:48.800 --> 00:11:50.880
if every entry is structured

00:11:50.880 --> 00:11:52.800
differently. The form is what makes

00:11:52.800 --> 00:11:54.959
automation possible. It's what is what

00:11:54.959 --> 00:11:57.279
lets the system compound like a good

00:11:57.279 --> 00:11:59.440
flywheel. The fourth building block is

00:11:59.440 --> 00:12:01.680
the filing cabinet. Engineers call this

00:12:01.680 --> 00:12:04.160
the memory store or the source of truth.

00:12:04.160 --> 00:12:06.320
It's where the system writes facts so

00:12:06.320 --> 00:12:09.200
that they can be reused later. It has to

00:12:09.200 --> 00:12:11.279
be writable by automation and readable

00:12:11.279 --> 00:12:13.600
by humans. And it has to support simple

00:12:13.600 --> 00:12:15.600
filters and views. So in this system,

00:12:15.600 --> 00:12:17.600
your filing cabinet is notion.

00:12:17.600 --> 00:12:19.440
Specifically, it's the four databases I

00:12:19.440 --> 00:12:20.720
talked about, right? It's people,

00:12:20.720 --> 00:12:22.800
project ideas, and admin. And notion

00:12:22.800 --> 00:12:24.880
databases are visual. They're really

00:12:24.880 --> 00:12:27.279
easy to edit without breaking anything.

00:12:27.279 --> 00:12:29.040
You can create different views filtered

00:12:29.040 --> 00:12:31.360
by status, by date, by tags. when

00:12:31.360 --> 00:12:32.959
something goes wrong, you can see what

00:12:32.959 --> 00:12:34.800
happened and fix it directly. And

00:12:34.800 --> 00:12:37.680
critically, Notion has a solid API that

00:12:37.680 --> 00:12:40.160
Zapier can write to reliably. The fifth

00:12:40.160 --> 00:12:42.720
building block is the receipt. Engineers

00:12:42.720 --> 00:12:44.880
call this an audit trail or a ledger.

00:12:44.880 --> 00:12:47.360
It's a record of what came in, what the

00:12:47.360 --> 00:12:49.200
system did with it, and how confident it

00:12:49.200 --> 00:12:50.800
was. And that matters more than a lot of

00:12:50.800 --> 00:12:52.480
us might realize. You don't really

00:12:52.480 --> 00:12:54.160
abandon systems because they're

00:12:54.160 --> 00:12:56.560
imperfect. You abandon them because you

00:12:56.560 --> 00:12:58.000
stop trusting them. And you stop

00:12:58.000 --> 00:12:59.760
trusting them because errors feel

00:12:59.760 --> 00:13:01.600
mysterious. something went wrong, but

00:13:01.600 --> 00:13:03.760
you don't know what or when or why, and

00:13:03.760 --> 00:13:05.120
you can't predict when the next error is

00:13:05.120 --> 00:13:06.480
going to happen, and you just give up.

00:13:06.480 --> 00:13:08.959
The receipt fixes that. In this system,

00:13:08.959 --> 00:13:11.040
your receipt is a notion database called

00:13:11.040 --> 00:13:13.360
inbox log. And every capture gets logged

00:13:13.360 --> 00:13:15.040
there with the original text that you

00:13:15.040 --> 00:13:17.040
typed, where it was filed, what it was

00:13:17.040 --> 00:13:18.560
named, and a confident score from the

00:13:18.560 --> 00:13:21.120
AI. And now when something looks off,

00:13:21.120 --> 00:13:23.040
you trace it. You can see what the

00:13:23.040 --> 00:13:25.440
system decided. You can see why comes

00:13:25.440 --> 00:13:27.360
from visibility, and visibility comes

00:13:27.360 --> 00:13:29.440
from logging. The sixth building block

00:13:29.440 --> 00:13:31.600
is the bouncer. Engineers call this a

00:13:31.600 --> 00:13:33.519
confidence filter or a guardrail. I like

00:13:33.519 --> 00:13:35.519
bouncer as a word. It's the mechanism

00:13:35.519 --> 00:13:37.600
that prevents lowquality outputs from

00:13:37.600 --> 00:13:39.360
polluting your memory storage. And

00:13:39.360 --> 00:13:41.200
here's how it works. When Claude or Chad

00:13:41.200 --> 00:13:43.600
GPT classifies your thought, it also

00:13:43.600 --> 00:13:45.360
returns a confidence score between zero

00:13:45.360 --> 00:13:47.680
and one. If that confidence is below a

00:13:47.680 --> 00:13:50.000
threshold, let's say 6, the system

00:13:50.000 --> 00:13:52.079
doesn't file it into people. It doesn't

00:13:52.079 --> 00:13:53.600
file it into projects. It doesn't file

00:13:53.600 --> 00:13:56.160
it into ideas. Instead, it logs it in

00:13:56.160 --> 00:13:58.399
inbox log with a status that says needs

00:13:58.399 --> 00:14:00.639
review and sends you a Slack reply

00:14:00.639 --> 00:14:03.440
asking for a clarification. I'm not sure

00:14:03.440 --> 00:14:05.440
where this goes. Can you repost it with

00:14:05.440 --> 00:14:07.920
a prefix like person or project or idea?

00:14:07.920 --> 00:14:09.920
I couldn't classify. This single

00:14:09.920 --> 00:14:11.920
mechanism is what keeps your second

00:14:11.920 --> 00:14:14.880
brain from becoming a junk drawer. The

00:14:14.880 --> 00:14:17.360
fastest way to kill a system is to fill

00:14:17.360 --> 00:14:19.519
it with garbage. The bouncer keeps

00:14:19.519 --> 00:14:21.120
things clean enough that you maintain

00:14:21.120 --> 00:14:23.360
trust, and trust is what keeps you using

00:14:23.360 --> 00:14:25.279
it. The seventh building block is the

00:14:25.279 --> 00:14:27.440
tap on the shoulder. Engineers call this

00:14:27.440 --> 00:14:30.079
proactive surfacing or notification.

00:14:30.079 --> 00:14:32.079
It's the system pushing useful

00:14:32.079 --> 00:14:34.480
information to you at the right time

00:14:34.480 --> 00:14:36.320
without you having to search for it. So

00:14:36.320 --> 00:14:37.920
in this system, the tap on the shoulder

00:14:37.920 --> 00:14:39.920
is a daily Slack DM that arrives at

00:14:39.920 --> 00:14:41.120
whatever time you want in the morning

00:14:41.120 --> 00:14:43.360
and is generated by a scheduled Zapier

00:14:43.360 --> 00:14:44.880
automation that queries your notion

00:14:44.880 --> 00:14:47.040
databases, pulls your active projects,

00:14:47.040 --> 00:14:49.199
any people with noted follow-ups, and

00:14:49.199 --> 00:14:51.279
sends that to Claude or Chad GPT with a

00:14:51.279 --> 00:14:52.800
summarization prompt, and then delivers

00:14:52.800 --> 00:14:54.480
a nice digest directly to your Slack

00:14:54.480 --> 00:14:56.160
DMs. And the digest will have three

00:14:56.160 --> 00:14:57.440
parts, right? It's going to have the top

00:14:57.440 --> 00:14:58.800
three actions for the day. It's going to

00:14:58.800 --> 00:15:00.079
have one thing you might be stuck on

00:15:00.079 --> 00:15:01.680
that you're avoiding and one small win

00:15:01.680 --> 00:15:03.680
to notice. It's designed to fit on a

00:15:03.680 --> 00:15:05.360
phone screen. It's designed for you to

00:15:05.360 --> 00:15:07.120
read it in 2 minutes, to know what

00:15:07.120 --> 00:15:09.040
matters today, and to start your day

00:15:09.040 --> 00:15:11.120
with confidence. And these nudges,

00:15:11.120 --> 00:15:13.120
they're not optional features. They're

00:15:13.120 --> 00:15:15.440
what makes this system alive instead of

00:15:15.440 --> 00:15:17.760
dead. Humans don't retrieve

00:15:17.760 --> 00:15:19.440
consistently. We don't wake up and

00:15:19.440 --> 00:15:21.040
think, I should search my notion

00:15:21.040 --> 00:15:23.120
databases for relevant information about

00:15:23.120 --> 00:15:24.720
the meeting I have today. In the

00:15:24.720 --> 00:15:26.480
advertisements, we do that, but we don't

00:15:26.480 --> 00:15:28.720
really do that. We do respond to what

00:15:28.720 --> 00:15:30.720
shows up in front of us. The tap on the

00:15:30.720 --> 00:15:32.880
shoulder exploits that. It puts the

00:15:32.880 --> 00:15:35.199
right information in your path so you

00:15:35.199 --> 00:15:37.120
don't have to remember to look for it.

00:15:37.120 --> 00:15:39.040
There's also a weekly version. Every

00:15:39.040 --> 00:15:41.519
Sunday at say whatever time, 4 p.m.

00:15:41.519 --> 00:15:42.720
whenever you want to have the Sunday

00:15:42.720 --> 00:15:44.560
scaries, right? Another Zapier

00:15:44.560 --> 00:15:46.560
automation runs. It queries everything

00:15:46.560 --> 00:15:48.720
from the past seven days in your inbox

00:15:48.720 --> 00:15:50.959
log, pulls your active projects, sends

00:15:50.959 --> 00:15:52.959
it all to Claude or chat GPT with a

00:15:52.959 --> 00:15:54.480
review prompt, and then delivers a

00:15:54.480 --> 00:15:56.880
weekly summary to your Slack DMs. And

00:15:56.880 --> 00:15:58.399
that summary, it'll tell you what

00:15:58.399 --> 00:15:59.680
happened. It tells you what your biggest

00:15:59.680 --> 00:16:02.000
open loops are. Three suggested actions

00:16:02.000 --> 00:16:03.920
for next week and one recurring theme

00:16:03.920 --> 00:16:05.680
that the system noticed. And so the

00:16:05.680 --> 00:16:07.759
Sunday review becomes a cadence that you

00:16:07.759 --> 00:16:09.839
can trust. It it's what turns storage

00:16:09.839 --> 00:16:12.240
into a consistent weekly direction. And

00:16:12.240 --> 00:16:13.680
without it, you're kind of just

00:16:13.680 --> 00:16:15.839
accumulating notes like the old way. The

00:16:15.839 --> 00:16:18.000
eighth building block is the fix button.

00:16:18.000 --> 00:16:19.519
Engineers would call this a feedback

00:16:19.519 --> 00:16:21.600
handle or a human in the loop correction

00:16:21.600 --> 00:16:24.160
mechanism. It's the one-step way to

00:16:24.160 --> 00:16:26.160
correct mistakes without opening

00:16:26.160 --> 00:16:27.839
dashboards or without trying to do

00:16:27.839 --> 00:16:29.839
maintenance. In this system, whenever

00:16:29.839 --> 00:16:31.759
the Zapier automation files something,

00:16:31.759 --> 00:16:33.440
it's going to reply in the Slack thread

00:16:33.440 --> 00:16:34.959
confirming what it did. Hey, this was

00:16:34.959 --> 00:16:36.720
filed as a project. The project is

00:16:36.720 --> 00:16:39.279
website relaunch. The confidence was 087

00:16:39.279 --> 00:16:41.279
reply fix if I got it wrong. If the

00:16:41.279 --> 00:16:43.279
filing was wrong, all you do is reply in

00:16:43.279 --> 00:16:45.199
the thread fix colon. This should be

00:16:45.199 --> 00:16:46.720
people, not projects. And the system

00:16:46.720 --> 00:16:48.480
will just update it. So why does that

00:16:48.480 --> 00:16:50.800
matter? Because systems get adopted when

00:16:50.800 --> 00:16:53.120
they're easy to repair. [snorts] If

00:16:53.120 --> 00:16:55.920
fixing errors feels like work if you

00:16:55.920 --> 00:16:58.240
have to open notion and navigate to the

00:16:58.240 --> 00:17:00.079
right database and find the entry and

00:17:00.079 --> 00:17:01.279
you're not going to do that. You're

00:17:01.279 --> 00:17:03.199
going to stop engaging. Corrections must

00:17:03.199 --> 00:17:05.600
be trivial or people will not make them.

00:17:05.600 --> 00:17:07.760
Now, let me give you the principles that

00:17:07.760 --> 00:17:09.919
make those building blocks actually

00:17:09.919 --> 00:17:11.439
work. These these are engineering

00:17:11.439 --> 00:17:13.039
principles, but they're not complicated.

00:17:13.039 --> 00:17:14.720
They're just rules that experienced

00:17:14.720 --> 00:17:16.160
system builders have learned. And when

00:17:16.160 --> 00:17:17.520
you understand them, you can build

00:17:17.520 --> 00:17:19.679
things that do not fall apart. Principle

00:17:19.679 --> 00:17:22.559
number one, reduce the human's job to

00:17:22.559 --> 00:17:24.959
one reliable behavior. If your system

00:17:24.959 --> 00:17:27.120
requires three behaviors, you don't have

00:17:27.120 --> 00:17:28.799
a system. You have a self-improvement

00:17:28.799 --> 00:17:31.120
program. And non-engineers will not run

00:17:31.120 --> 00:17:33.039
those programs very consistently. The

00:17:33.039 --> 00:17:34.799
scalable move is to make the human do

00:17:34.799 --> 00:17:36.320
one thing, which in this case is capture

00:17:36.320 --> 00:17:38.000
it in Slack. Everything else is

00:17:38.000 --> 00:17:40.160
automation. Classification is Claude or

00:17:40.160 --> 00:17:42.000
Chad GPT doing the work and filing is

00:17:42.000 --> 00:17:43.840
Zapier doing the work and surfacing is a

00:17:43.840 --> 00:17:45.679
scheduled automation. You get the idea.

00:17:45.679 --> 00:17:47.600
The human's job is just to throw

00:17:47.600 --> 00:17:49.760
thoughts at the channel. That's it.

00:17:49.760 --> 00:17:52.000
Principle number two, separate memory

00:17:52.000 --> 00:17:54.400
from compute and from interface. This is

00:17:54.400 --> 00:17:56.240
the single most important architectural

00:17:56.240 --> 00:17:57.440
principle and it's how you build

00:17:57.440 --> 00:17:59.520
something that lasts. Memory is where

00:17:59.520 --> 00:18:01.360
truth lives. That's your notion database

00:18:01.360 --> 00:18:03.440
in this system. Compute is where the

00:18:03.440 --> 00:18:05.360
logic run. That's zap year and that's

00:18:05.360 --> 00:18:07.520
claude. Interface is where the human

00:18:07.520 --> 00:18:09.679
interacts. That's in Slack. Why would we

00:18:09.679 --> 00:18:11.600
separate those? Because it makes the

00:18:11.600 --> 00:18:14.080
system portable and swappable. You can

00:18:14.080 --> 00:18:16.000
change your interface from Slack to

00:18:16.000 --> 00:18:17.840
Microsoft Teams without rebuilding

00:18:17.840 --> 00:18:20.000
everything. You can swap Claude for Chad

00:18:20.000 --> 00:18:22.400
GPT without touching your databases. You

00:18:22.400 --> 00:18:24.160
can move from notion to Air Table if

00:18:24.160 --> 00:18:25.679
your company wants you to or if you feel

00:18:25.679 --> 00:18:28.080
like it. Every layer has just one job

00:18:28.080 --> 00:18:29.280
and they connect through clear

00:18:29.280 --> 00:18:31.280
boundaries. This is also why I don't

00:18:31.280 --> 00:18:33.039
recommend starting with Obsidian if

00:18:33.039 --> 00:18:34.640
you're a non-engineer, even though

00:18:34.640 --> 00:18:37.120
Obsidian is a beautiful tool. Obsidian

00:18:37.120 --> 00:18:39.039
stores everything as local markdown

00:18:39.039 --> 00:18:40.400
files, which is really great for

00:18:40.400 --> 00:18:42.080
portability. It's great for ownership,

00:18:42.080 --> 00:18:44.400
but writing into local files from cloud

00:18:44.400 --> 00:18:46.480
automation introduces a layer of syncing

00:18:46.480 --> 00:18:48.559
and plumbing that may seem trivial for

00:18:48.559 --> 00:18:50.080
engineers, but I find is often

00:18:50.080 --> 00:18:52.400
frustrating for everybody else. So,

00:18:52.400 --> 00:18:53.679
starting with notion makes that

00:18:53.679 --> 00:18:55.120
automation really clean, and you can

00:18:55.120 --> 00:18:56.320
always migrate later if you want

00:18:56.320 --> 00:18:58.000
something that's local first. Principle

00:18:58.000 --> 00:19:00.559
number three, treat prompts like APIs,

00:19:00.559 --> 00:19:02.720
not like creative writing. A scalable

00:19:02.720 --> 00:19:05.360
agentic prompt is a contract. It's a

00:19:05.360 --> 00:19:07.360
fixed input format. It's a fixed output

00:19:07.360 --> 00:19:09.039
format. It's no surprises. You give

00:19:09.039 --> 00:19:11.039
Claude or Chad GPT a schema. You give it

00:19:11.039 --> 00:19:12.720
rules and you tell it to return JSON

00:19:12.720 --> 00:19:14.640
only with no explanation and no

00:19:14.640 --> 00:19:16.799
markdown. That feels restrictive and

00:19:16.799 --> 00:19:18.400
that's the whole point. You don't want

00:19:18.400 --> 00:19:20.240
the model to be helpful in uncontrolled

00:19:20.240 --> 00:19:21.840
ways in this system. You want it to fill

00:19:21.840 --> 00:19:25.360
out a form. The prompt specifies exactly

00:19:25.360 --> 00:19:27.360
what fields to return, exactly what

00:19:27.360 --> 00:19:29.120
values are valid, and exactly how to

00:19:29.120 --> 00:19:31.520
handle ambiguous cases. Reliable beats

00:19:31.520 --> 00:19:33.440
creative in these systems. And it's

00:19:33.440 --> 00:19:35.120
really important to remember that as you

00:19:35.120 --> 00:19:37.360
start to build things. Principle four,

00:19:37.360 --> 00:19:40.400
always build a trust mechanism, not just

00:19:40.400 --> 00:19:42.480
a capability. So a capability is the bot

00:19:42.480 --> 00:19:43.760
files the notes, right? A trust

00:19:43.760 --> 00:19:46.160
mechanism is I believe the filing enough

00:19:46.160 --> 00:19:48.559
to keep using it because and so trust

00:19:48.559 --> 00:19:50.480
comes from the inbox log that shows you

00:19:50.480 --> 00:19:52.160
everything that happened. Confidence

00:19:52.160 --> 00:19:54.400
scores from the fix button that makes

00:19:54.400 --> 00:19:56.559
corrections trivial. Without these small

00:19:56.559 --> 00:19:58.480
things, you might think the system would

00:19:58.480 --> 00:20:00.480
still function, but small errors tend to

00:20:00.480 --> 00:20:02.480
compound. And with them, the system

00:20:02.480 --> 00:20:03.840
actually can learn and earn your

00:20:03.840 --> 00:20:05.600
confidence over time. Principle number

00:20:05.600 --> 00:20:07.600
five, you want to default to safe

00:20:07.600 --> 00:20:10.160
behavior when uncertain. A real agentic

00:20:10.160 --> 00:20:12.400
system has to know how to fail

00:20:12.400 --> 00:20:14.720
gracefully. The safest default is when

00:20:14.720 --> 00:20:16.559
Claude or Chad GPT isn't sure is you

00:20:16.559 --> 00:20:18.799
just log the item and write that Slack

00:20:18.799 --> 00:20:21.200
message and ask for clarification. And

00:20:21.200 --> 00:20:23.120
that's exactly why we have a confidence

00:20:23.120 --> 00:20:24.880
threshold. When confidence is below

00:20:24.880 --> 00:20:26.160
whatever number you select, I'm

00:20:26.160 --> 00:20:28.720
suggesting 6. It doesn't file. It just

00:20:28.720 --> 00:20:31.360
holds. It asks. It might seem boring,

00:20:31.360 --> 00:20:33.200
but it's essential to build trust.

00:20:33.200 --> 00:20:36.960
Principle number six, make output small,

00:20:36.960 --> 00:20:39.760
frequent, and actionable. Non-engineers

00:20:39.760 --> 00:20:42.080
don't want a weekly 2,000word analysis,

00:20:42.080 --> 00:20:43.440
right? They want a top three list that

00:20:43.440 --> 00:20:45.039
fits on a phone screen. Frankly, most

00:20:45.039 --> 00:20:47.440
engineers do, too. They want a Slack DM

00:20:47.440 --> 00:20:48.960
they can read in 2 minutes. Most

00:20:48.960 --> 00:20:51.440
engineers do, too. Small outputs reduce

00:20:51.440 --> 00:20:52.960
cognitive load and increase

00:20:52.960 --> 00:20:55.200
follow-through. So, the daily digest

00:20:55.200 --> 00:20:57.760
needs to be under 150 words, and the

00:20:57.760 --> 00:21:00.640
weekly review needs to be under 250

00:21:00.640 --> 00:21:03.200
words. That's very intentional. Agentic

00:21:03.200 --> 00:21:04.960
systems scale when they produce very

00:21:04.960 --> 00:21:06.880
useful outputs that are small but

00:21:06.880 --> 00:21:09.280
extremely reliable on a set cadence. And

00:21:09.280 --> 00:21:10.960
then at the end of the day, you start

00:21:10.960 --> 00:21:12.320
trusting them because you're essentially

00:21:12.320 --> 00:21:14.559
getting a breadcrumb of trust and value

00:21:14.559 --> 00:21:16.640
every time you use it. Principle number

00:21:16.640 --> 00:21:19.919
seven, use next action as the unit of

00:21:19.919 --> 00:21:21.679
execution. So what I mean by that is

00:21:21.679 --> 00:21:23.600
most project notes fail because they

00:21:23.600 --> 00:21:26.159
store intentions, not actions. Work on

00:21:26.159 --> 00:21:28.400
the website is not executable. Email

00:21:28.400 --> 00:21:30.320
Sarah to confirm the copy deadline is

00:21:30.320 --> 00:21:32.320
very executable. And so that's why the

00:21:32.320 --> 00:21:34.320
project database will need to have a

00:21:34.320 --> 00:21:36.159
field called next action. And the

00:21:36.159 --> 00:21:39.679
classification prompt needs to be tuned

00:21:39.679 --> 00:21:42.960
to extract very specific actions from

00:21:42.960 --> 00:21:44.799
what is probably a vague statement on

00:21:44.799 --> 00:21:46.400
your part because if your project

00:21:46.400 --> 00:21:48.159
entries don't have concrete actions,

00:21:48.159 --> 00:21:50.000
your daily digest is going to end up

00:21:50.000 --> 00:21:51.600
feeling motivational rather than

00:21:51.600 --> 00:21:54.080
operational. And this is all about

00:21:54.080 --> 00:21:56.000
helping you be more operational in a way

00:21:56.000 --> 00:21:58.080
that's reliable without you having to

00:21:58.080 --> 00:21:59.679
put more cognitive work into it.

00:21:59.679 --> 00:22:02.480
Principle eight, prefer routing over

00:22:02.480 --> 00:22:05.120
organizing. Humans hate organizing. Most

00:22:05.120 --> 00:22:07.360
of us, not all of us, most of us. Most

00:22:07.360 --> 00:22:09.039
of us like dropping things in a box and

00:22:09.039 --> 00:22:11.039
forgetting about them. Claude is good at

00:22:11.039 --> 00:22:13.120
routing. Chai GBT is good at routing.

00:22:13.120 --> 00:22:14.960
The principle is don't make users

00:22:14.960 --> 00:22:17.200
maintain structures. Let the system

00:22:17.200 --> 00:22:18.799
route into a small set of stable

00:22:18.799 --> 00:22:20.640
buckets. And that's why the system I'm

00:22:20.640 --> 00:22:22.000
suggesting has really only four

00:22:22.000 --> 00:22:24.000
categories: people, projects, ideas, and

00:22:24.000 --> 00:22:26.720
admin. More categories can feel more

00:22:26.720 --> 00:22:28.559
precise, but can be much harder to

00:22:28.559 --> 00:22:30.799
scale. It creates more decisions, more

00:22:30.799 --> 00:22:32.960
confusion, more drift. Four buckets is

00:22:32.960 --> 00:22:34.400
usually enough. You can always add more

00:22:34.400 --> 00:22:36.880
later if you really discover a need.

00:22:36.880 --> 00:22:38.960
Principle nine, keep the number of

00:22:38.960 --> 00:22:41.600
categories and fields painfully small.

00:22:41.600 --> 00:22:43.360
This is counterintuitive for smart

00:22:43.360 --> 00:22:45.360
people. We we want richness. We want

00:22:45.360 --> 00:22:47.520
nuance, but richness creates friction,

00:22:47.520 --> 00:22:50.480
and friction kills adoption. So, the

00:22:50.480 --> 00:22:52.480
people database, I'm suggesting it has

00:22:52.480 --> 00:22:54.320
like just a few fields, right? the

00:22:54.320 --> 00:22:56.080
person's name, the last time you

00:22:56.080 --> 00:22:58.080
connected with them, the ideas database,

00:22:58.080 --> 00:23:00.320
five fields at most. And the idea is if

00:23:00.320 --> 00:23:02.240
you have minimal fields, you can always

00:23:02.240 --> 00:23:04.480
add sophistication later. But if you

00:23:04.480 --> 00:23:06.640
start simple and stay simple, it gives

00:23:06.640 --> 00:23:08.480
you the option to continue to use the

00:23:08.480 --> 00:23:10.159
system, and you only have to add

00:23:10.159 --> 00:23:12.480
complexity when evidence says it's

00:23:12.480 --> 00:23:15.600
needed. Principle 10, build your design

00:23:15.600 --> 00:23:17.919
for restart, not for perfection. A

00:23:17.919 --> 00:23:20.159
scalable system assumes users will fall

00:23:20.159 --> 00:23:22.559
off. Life happens, you get sick, you

00:23:22.559 --> 00:23:24.559
travel, you have a rough week at work.

00:23:24.559 --> 00:23:26.559
The system should be easy to restart

00:23:26.559 --> 00:23:28.720
without guilt or cleanup. If missing a

00:23:28.720 --> 00:23:30.480
week creates some kind of backlog

00:23:30.480 --> 00:23:32.320
monster, you're not going to restart.

00:23:32.320 --> 00:23:33.440
You're just going to feel bad about

00:23:33.440 --> 00:23:34.960
yourself. And so, that's why the

00:23:34.960 --> 00:23:36.640
operating manual for this system

00:23:36.640 --> 00:23:39.600
explicitly says, "Don't catch up. Just

00:23:39.600 --> 00:23:42.000
restart. Do a 10-minute brain dump into

00:23:42.000 --> 00:23:43.760
your inbox with whatever you've got and

00:23:43.760 --> 00:23:45.679
resume tomorrow." And the automation

00:23:45.679 --> 00:23:46.960
will keep things running whether you

00:23:46.960 --> 00:23:49.440
engage or not. the system waits for you

00:23:49.440 --> 00:23:50.960
and is supportive and is easy to

00:23:50.960 --> 00:23:54.240
restart. Principle 11, build one

00:23:54.240 --> 00:23:56.640
workflow and then attach modules. So the

00:23:56.640 --> 00:23:58.559
scalable pattern is to build a core loop

00:23:58.559 --> 00:24:00.320
that works for everybody and then add

00:24:00.320 --> 00:24:02.400
optional capabilities later. And so the

00:24:02.400 --> 00:24:04.480
core loop is capture to Slack, file to

00:24:04.480 --> 00:24:06.720
notion, get a daily digest, get a weekly

00:24:06.720 --> 00:24:09.440
review. That's the minimum viable loop

00:24:09.440 --> 00:24:11.039
here. And once that's running, once you

00:24:11.039 --> 00:24:12.960
trust it, you can add voice capture if

00:24:12.960 --> 00:24:14.480
you want. You can add meeting prep by

00:24:14.480 --> 00:24:15.840
integrating it with your calendar. You

00:24:15.840 --> 00:24:17.600
can add email forwarding. You can add

00:24:17.600 --> 00:24:19.520
birthday reminders, but you don't do

00:24:19.520 --> 00:24:21.200
that first. You build the core loop

00:24:21.200 --> 00:24:24.159
first. Principle 12, optimize for

00:24:24.159 --> 00:24:27.120
maintainability over cleverness. So the

00:24:27.120 --> 00:24:28.720
engineering temptation is to build a

00:24:28.720 --> 00:24:30.480
beautiful system with so many moving

00:24:30.480 --> 00:24:32.159
parts and elegant abstractions. And the

00:24:32.159 --> 00:24:34.000
real world reality is that moving parts

00:24:34.000 --> 00:24:36.240
are failure points. And so optimize for

00:24:36.240 --> 00:24:39.039
fewer tools, fewer steps, clear logs,

00:24:39.039 --> 00:24:41.120
easy reconnects. When your Zapier

00:24:41.120 --> 00:24:42.799
automation stops because your Slack

00:24:42.799 --> 00:24:44.720
token expired, which is a real thing,

00:24:44.720 --> 00:24:46.559
you want to fix it in five minutes, not

00:24:46.559 --> 00:24:48.480
debug it for an hour. And when notion

00:24:48.480 --> 00:24:49.840
permissions get weird, you want to

00:24:49.840 --> 00:24:51.760
reconnect and move on. That's what makes

00:24:51.760 --> 00:24:54.000
this actually scale. Now, I often get

00:24:54.000 --> 00:24:55.520
complaints on these videos that I don't

00:24:55.520 --> 00:24:57.520
give enough detail. No complaints here.

00:24:57.520 --> 00:24:58.880
I'm going to walk you through step by

00:24:58.880 --> 00:25:01.120
step what we're doing. First, create the

00:25:01.120 --> 00:25:02.799
Slack channel. Go to Slack. Create a new

00:25:02.799 --> 00:25:04.080
channel called Whatever You Want. Make

00:25:04.080 --> 00:25:05.679
it private if you wish. And pin a

00:25:05.679 --> 00:25:07.279
message that explain what goes there.

00:25:07.279 --> 00:25:08.799
Something like, "Drop a thought here.

00:25:08.799 --> 00:25:11.279
one thought per message etc. Second, you

00:25:11.279 --> 00:25:13.440
want to create the notion databases. You

00:25:13.440 --> 00:25:14.960
want to create a new page called second

00:25:14.960 --> 00:25:16.480
brain and inside it you want to create

00:25:16.480 --> 00:25:19.360
your five databases as table people

00:25:19.360 --> 00:25:22.480
might have name context follow-ups last

00:25:22.480 --> 00:25:26.159
touched tags project status next action

00:25:26.159 --> 00:25:28.480
notes ideas could have name and oneliner

00:25:28.480 --> 00:25:30.000
and yes there there's there's going to

00:25:30.000 --> 00:25:31.760
be a whole worksheet for you if you want

00:25:31.760 --> 00:25:33.039
to get this in the substacks you don't

00:25:33.039 --> 00:25:34.159
have to remember this but I'm just going

00:25:34.159 --> 00:25:35.840
through the detail right you want to

00:25:35.840 --> 00:25:37.520
have uh the name of the idea the

00:25:37.520 --> 00:25:39.840
oneliner the notes the tags etc and

00:25:39.840 --> 00:25:41.600
admin would have the name the due date

00:25:41.600 --> 00:25:44.240
the status etc inbox log. It has to have

00:25:44.240 --> 00:25:46.799
captured text file to destination record

00:25:46.799 --> 00:25:48.080
the confidence level when it was

00:25:48.080 --> 00:25:50.159
created. Third, you connect Zapier to

00:25:50.159 --> 00:25:52.000
Slack and to Notion to make that pipe.

00:25:52.000 --> 00:25:53.440
So you go to Zapier, you connect your

00:25:53.440 --> 00:25:54.880
Slack account, you connect your notion

00:25:54.880 --> 00:25:56.640
account, and when notion asks which

00:25:56.640 --> 00:25:58.640
pages Zapier can access, make sure you

00:25:58.640 --> 00:26:00.320
grant access to the right page. Fourth,

00:26:00.320 --> 00:26:01.840
you want to build the automation. So

00:26:01.840 --> 00:26:04.159
create a new zap and the trigger is new

00:26:04.159 --> 00:26:06.240
message posted to channel in the Slack

00:26:06.240 --> 00:26:07.679
and it's filtered to just that one

00:26:07.679 --> 00:26:10.080
channel you want like SP inbox. The next

00:26:10.080 --> 00:26:12.159
step is an AI action that sends the

00:26:12.159 --> 00:26:14.320
message to Claude or Chad GBT with your

00:26:14.320 --> 00:26:16.799
classification prompt. The prompt tells

00:26:16.799 --> 00:26:18.480
it to classify into people, project

00:26:18.480 --> 00:26:20.400
ideas or admin and yes, I'll supply this

00:26:20.400 --> 00:26:22.240
prompt and then it returns JSON. And

00:26:22.240 --> 00:26:23.600
then the next step, you're just parsing

00:26:23.600 --> 00:26:25.520
that JSON. You add paths that route

00:26:25.520 --> 00:26:26.880
based on the destination. If it's

00:26:26.880 --> 00:26:28.400
people, create a record in the people

00:26:28.400 --> 00:26:30.080
database. If it's projects, you create

00:26:30.080 --> 00:26:32.000
in projects and so on. Fifth, you want

00:26:32.000 --> 00:26:33.360
to build your morning digest. Create

00:26:33.360 --> 00:26:35.120
another zap. The triggers a daily

00:26:35.120 --> 00:26:36.400
schedule at whatever time in the

00:26:36.400 --> 00:26:37.919
morning. the action queries your notion

00:26:37.919 --> 00:26:40.080
database and you send that query result

00:26:40.080 --> 00:26:41.679
to claude or chat GPT with a

00:26:41.679 --> 00:26:43.120
summarization prompt. Again, I'll

00:26:43.120 --> 00:26:45.039
provide the summarization prompt. Then

00:26:45.039 --> 00:26:46.640
you can build the weekly review with the

00:26:46.640 --> 00:26:48.480
same pattern. That's the whole system.

00:26:48.480 --> 00:26:50.720
It's three Zapier automations. It's four

00:26:50.720 --> 00:26:53.200
notion databases plus a log. It's one

00:26:53.200 --> 00:26:55.440
channel. Look, it might not even take an

00:26:55.440 --> 00:26:57.360
hour to set this up. And maybe it'll

00:26:57.360 --> 00:26:58.640
take 90 minutes if you're comfortable

00:26:58.640 --> 00:27:00.400
with Zapier. Now, let me tell you what

00:27:00.400 --> 00:27:01.600
this will feel like when it's working,

00:27:01.600 --> 00:27:04.400
though. You will feel lighter. It's not

00:27:04.400 --> 00:27:06.080
because you're more productive in some

00:27:06.080 --> 00:27:07.919
fantastically measurable way. It's

00:27:07.919 --> 00:27:09.919
because you're closing all of the open

00:27:09.919 --> 00:27:11.520
loops that are living in your head

00:27:11.520 --> 00:27:13.440
constantly. And you'll notice yourself

00:27:13.440 --> 00:27:14.960
thinking, I should remember that. And

00:27:14.960 --> 00:27:16.559
instead of trying to leave it as an open

00:27:16.559 --> 00:27:18.559
loop in your head, you're going to post

00:27:18.559 --> 00:27:21.039
it into your SB inbox and move along

00:27:21.039 --> 00:27:23.120
because you don't have to think about it

00:27:23.120 --> 00:27:24.880
anymore. And so your head will get

00:27:24.880 --> 00:27:26.559
clearer. And so you're going to notice

00:27:26.559 --> 00:27:28.480
that you're able to show up with more

00:27:28.480 --> 00:27:30.159
continuity for the people that matter to

00:27:30.159 --> 00:27:31.600
you, for the projects that matter to

00:27:31.600 --> 00:27:33.039
you, for the work. you'll have an easier

00:27:33.039 --> 00:27:35.039
time remembering details. And then as

00:27:35.039 --> 00:27:37.200
you go along and use it more, you're

00:27:37.200 --> 00:27:38.960
going to start to compound because the

00:27:38.960 --> 00:27:40.400
projects are going to start to develop

00:27:40.400 --> 00:27:42.480
patterns that you can see and notice

00:27:42.480 --> 00:27:44.240
over time. And that's going to enable

00:27:44.240 --> 00:27:46.640
you to get smarter about giving input

00:27:46.640 --> 00:27:48.640
back to the system through SP inbox.

00:27:48.640 --> 00:27:50.799
Your anxiety, if you're someone who

00:27:50.799 --> 00:27:52.720
tries to remember everything, it doesn't

00:27:52.720 --> 00:27:54.399
magically go away entirely, but it

00:27:54.399 --> 00:27:56.559
definitely changes in character. It

00:27:56.559 --> 00:27:58.720
stops being just this background hum of

00:27:58.720 --> 00:28:00.799
all of your unttracked commitments and

00:28:00.799 --> 00:28:02.480
it starts being a small set of next

00:28:02.480 --> 00:28:05.360
actions that you can actually take. It's

00:28:05.360 --> 00:28:07.760
basically a a factory for turning your

00:28:07.760 --> 00:28:09.360
anxiety and your difficulty in

00:28:09.360 --> 00:28:11.600
remembering things into action. Now, I

00:28:11.600 --> 00:28:13.760
got to be honest with you. I am going to

00:28:13.760 --> 00:28:15.919
give you this video and most people will

00:28:15.919 --> 00:28:17.679
not actually build this. Not because

00:28:17.679 --> 00:28:19.840
it's hard. You've heard me describe it.

00:28:19.840 --> 00:28:22.080
It doesn't take that long. It's because

00:28:22.080 --> 00:28:24.880
we've normalized the leakage that comes

00:28:24.880 --> 00:28:26.399
from being busy. We scroll through

00:28:26.399 --> 00:28:28.399
YouTube, it's like, ah, Nate's saying

00:28:28.399 --> 00:28:29.600
something again, he'll come up with

00:28:29.600 --> 00:28:31.840
another video. I want you to think about

00:28:31.840 --> 00:28:35.360
it as the cost of a system that we fail

00:28:35.360 --> 00:28:38.080
to build isn't just missed ideas. It's

00:28:38.080 --> 00:28:40.640
that your work becomes less compounding.

00:28:40.640 --> 00:28:45.200
The value you create in 2026 is lower

00:28:45.200 --> 00:28:47.039
because you're not building on that

00:28:47.039 --> 00:28:48.960
value as intentionally as you could be.

00:28:48.960 --> 00:28:50.240
And so, if you're watching this in

00:28:50.240 --> 00:28:51.600
January and you're thinking about what

00:28:51.600 --> 00:28:53.679
project might actually change the year,

00:28:53.679 --> 00:28:55.120
think about doing this one, right?

00:28:55.120 --> 00:28:56.720
You're not building a productivity

00:28:56.720 --> 00:28:58.240
system. You're not building something to

00:28:58.240 --> 00:29:00.240
feel good about yourself. You're just

00:29:00.240 --> 00:29:03.120
relentlessly taking charge of your

00:29:03.120 --> 00:29:05.600
actual brain and giving it a support

00:29:05.600 --> 00:29:07.039
system that helps it to work

00:29:07.039 --> 00:29:08.720
effectively. And for the first time in

00:29:08.720 --> 00:29:10.880
human history, you have access to

00:29:10.880 --> 00:29:13.279
systems that will work for you while you

00:29:13.279 --> 00:29:15.200
sleep. That classify your thoughts

00:29:15.200 --> 00:29:17.440
without you deciding, that surface the

00:29:17.440 --> 00:29:19.360
right information without you searching,

00:29:19.360 --> 00:29:21.840
that nudge you toward the goals and

00:29:21.840 --> 00:29:24.159
priorities you've set without you having

00:29:24.159 --> 00:29:25.919
to remember them. And you don't even

00:29:25.919 --> 00:29:27.600
have to be an engineer to build this.

00:29:27.600 --> 00:29:29.279
You just have to understand patterns.

00:29:29.279 --> 00:29:31.039
And that's exactly what I've laid out in

00:29:31.039 --> 00:29:33.039
this video. So that's the whole

00:29:33.039 --> 00:29:35.840
architecture. And in 2026, you can build

00:29:35.840 --> 00:29:38.080
it yourself. And yes, I have all of the

00:29:38.080 --> 00:29:40.080
guides for this on the Substack. I hope

00:29:40.080 --> 00:29:41.840
this has been helpful. I want everyone

00:29:41.840 --> 00:29:43.919
to feel like one, they can build

00:29:43.919 --> 00:29:46.320
something with AI. Two, it's worth

00:29:46.320 --> 00:29:49.440
doing. Three, if you build smartly, you

00:29:49.440 --> 00:29:51.600
are building in a way that allows you to

00:29:51.600 --> 00:29:53.360
compound your advantage over time, which

00:29:53.360 --> 00:29:55.039
is going to be really important as AI

00:29:55.039 --> 00:29:57.440
moves faster in 2026. So, that's how to

00:29:57.440 --> 00:29:59.279
build a second brain without a line of

00:29:59.279 --> 00:30:01.200
code. And those are the engineering

00:30:01.200 --> 00:30:02.960
principles that you're using even if

00:30:02.960 --> 00:30:04.559
you're not an engineer. Hope you enjoyed

00:30:04.559 --> 00:30:07.120
this one.
